abstract: Andrés Manuel López Obrador, Mexico’s incoming president, has a reputation for defending the poor. President Trump is already testing whether he will live up to it.
snippet: Andrés Manuel López Obrador, Mexico’s incoming president, has a reputation for defending the poor. President Trump is already testing whether he will live up to it.
lead_paragraph: Good Tuesday morning. Here are some of the stories making news in Washington and politics today.
headline_main: On Politics: Trump and Mexico’s New Leader Square Off Over Migrants

abstract: The Minnesota senator emerged unscathed from the Kavanaugh hearings, then coasted to a third term. Now she is weighing whether her home state appeal can translate nationally.
snippet: The Minnesota senator emerged unscathed from the Kavanaugh hearings, then coasted to a third term. Now she is weighing whether her home state appeal can translate nationally.
lead_paragraph: NORTHFIELD, Minn. — The speculation began the moment Senator Amy Klobuchar walked into the room.

abstract: Lawmakers return this week to a host of pressing major issues, including a farm bill and a potential government shutdown, and a narrow window to act.
snippet: Lawmakers return this week to a host of pressing major issues, including a farm bill and a potential government shutdown, and a narrow window to act.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Lawmakers returning to Capitol Hill this week face a reckoning with an unwelcome reality of a gridlocked Washington: the lame-duck session’s growing pile of unresolved, but critical, legislation and a narrow window to act.

abstract: In one industry after another, big companies have become more dominant over the past 15 years, new data show.
snippet: In one industry after another, big companies have become more dominant over the past 15 years, new data show.
lead_paragraph: The popular telling of the Boston Tea Party gets something wrong. The colonists were not responding to a tax increase. They were responding to the Tea Act of 1773, which granted a tea monopoly in the colonies to the well-connected East India Company. Merchants based in the Americas would be shut out of the market.

abstract: Tech giants have found key allies among Democrats for years, a bond strengthened through mutual interests and campaign donations. But a year of scandals has forced a reckoning in Washington.
snippet: Tech giants have found key allies among Democrats for years, a bond strengthened through mutual interests and campaign donations. But a year of scandals has forced a reckoning in Washington.
lead_paragraph: The alliance between Democrats and Silicon Valley has buckled and bent this year amid revelations that platforms like Facebook and Twitter allowed hateful speech, Russian propaganda and conservative-leaning “fake news” to flourish.

abstract: Mr. Zuckerberg said that he wouldn’t step down as chairman and that his No. 2, Sheryl Sandberg, was “doing great work” despite questions about their management.
snippet: Mr. Zuckerberg said that he wouldn’t step down as chairman and that his No. 2, Sheryl Sandberg, was “doing great work” despite questions about their management.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — On Thursday, Mark Zuckerberg, Facebook’s chief executive and chairman, held a conference call with reporters to discuss how the social network manages problematic posts and its community standards.

abstract: An investigation by The New York Times revealed how Facebook fought back against critics during a flood of crises — with delays, denials and an influence campaign in Washington.
snippet: An investigation by The New York Times revealed how Facebook fought back against critics during a flood of crises — with delays, denials and an influence campaign in Washington.
lead_paragraph: For more than a year, Facebook has endured cascading crises — over Russian misinformation, data privacy and abusive content — that transformed the Silicon Valley icon into an embattled giant accused of corporate overreach and negligence.

abstract: For the first time, four of the top elected statewide officials will be women who ran on a broad range of issues.
snippet: For the first time, four of the top elected statewide officials will be women who ran on a broad range of issues.
lead_paragraph: The first time I ran for office, for a seat on my county board of commissioners, I was 24 years old. I didn’t have a lot of political experience. What I did have was a cause I believed in — keeping the local nursing home open — and the willingness to work really hard. My opponent in the race, an older male incumbent, derisively referred to me as “that young broad.” That young broad beat him.
